(generally) in re: =E2=80=9Cfit models=E2=80=9D instead of fitness function=
s. John von Neumann remarked, =E2=80=9CThe sciences do not try to explain, =
they hardly even try to interpret, they mainly make models. By a model is m=
eant a mathematical construct which, with the addition of certain verbal in=
terpretations, describes observed phenomena. The justification of such a ma=
thematical construct is solely and precisely that it is expected to work.=
=E2=80=9D



Contexts might be physical environments, financial (flows of =
monies), economic (flows of values), technical, legal, socio-societal, poli=
tical, etc. aspects. When we discover models that =E2=80=9Cfit=E2=80=9D WRT=
 data, we must go further (Inverse Theory) to discover plausibility and lik=
elihood in those contexts. There is a history of models (ANNs or CPPNs that=
 generated them) that didn=E2=80=99t work well in the past. These need be r=
evisited =E2=80=9Cevery so often=E2=80=9D, as do totally novel models (and,=
 of course, new data) that haven=E2=80=99t been evaluated. Topologically, =
=E2=80=9Cinteresting=E2=80=9D can be sheaves =E2=80=9Cnear the site of=E2=
=80=9D particular locations or equi-distant away from those sites.



