If you are asking whether we t=
ried rewarding agents only for visiting locations that yield a real game re=
ward, or only for visiting locations that are known to be instrumental towa=
rds obtaining such rewards=E2=80=94we did not. The latter idea was investig=
ated in Kulkarni et al.&#39;s hierarchical RL (https://arxiv.org/abs/1604.06057=
), which manually determined several important stepping stones to be reache=
d: in Montezuma&#39;s Revenge, these were the 3 ladders, the key, and both door=
s of the first room. By rewarding for important intermediate states (e.g. t=
he agent must descend several ladders before picking up the key, which is n=
ecessary for solving the game), that work was able to explore the first 1-2=
 rooms of Montezuma&#39;s Revenge=E2=80=94but no more, due to the difficulty of=
 hand-designing the intermediate goals.

In contrast, our work does not mak=
e any assumptions about which states are important. Agents are equally rewa=
rded for visiting any new location (and the order of exploration does not a=
ffect any received intrinsic rewards).

If this is not what you meant, plea=
se let me know so I can better answer your question.


